    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <!-- 1. TITLE PAGE -->
    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <div class="title-page">
        <div class="title">KalaVaras — कलावारस</div>
        <div class="subtitle">Folk Art Motor Memory Platform</div>
        <hr style="width: 100px; border: 1px solid #E8593C; margin: 30px auto;">
        <div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold; color: #2D1B69;">Complete Technical Reference & Architecture Guide</div>
        <div class="metadata">
            <strong>Author:</strong> Technical Documentation Specialist<br>
            <strong>Version:</strong> 1.0 (Innovation Portfolio Edition)<br>
            <strong>Core Platform:</strong> React 18, Node.js 20, Flask, FFmpeg<br>
            <strong>Databases:</strong> PostgreSQL 18 & PGLite (WASM SQLite)<br>
            <strong>Deployment Target:</strong> Vercel & Render
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <!-- 2. PROJECT OVERVIEW -->
    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <h1>1. Project Overview & Product Vision</h1>
    <p>
        <strong>KalaVaras</strong> ("Art Heir" in Marathi) is a bilingual (Marathi and English) digital platform built to capture the invisible motor memory of master artisans in traditional Indian folk art styles—specifically <strong>Warli</strong>, <strong>Kolam</strong>, <strong>Pichwai</strong>, and <strong>Madhubani</strong>—and transfer this embodied knowledge to young apprentices.
    </p>
    <p>
        Unlike finished art portfolios, which only preserve static outcomes, KalaVaras captures the dynamics of creation: the pressure, speed, trajectory, and rhythm of the hand. It serves as a living innovation portfolio showing how design thinking, motor learning neuroscience, and appropriate technology can preserve endangered cultural heritage in rural Maharashtra.
    </p>

    <h2>1.1 The Gaps KalaVaras Addresses</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Documentation Gap:</strong> Existing digital archives preserve only high-resolution static images of final paintings. They fail to record the stroke trajectory, velocity profile, and drawing mechanics that define a tradition.</li>
        <li><strong>Technology Gap:</strong> Professional motion capture setups (using specialized gloves or infrared sensors) are expensive, fragile, and inaccessible in rural communities. KalaVaras uses simple, web-based webcam tracking.</li>
        <li><strong>Pedagogy Gap:</strong> Remote apprentices often learn from static images or low-resolution video clips sent over messaging apps, which lacks structure and real-time guidance. KalaVaras provides step-by-step guidance and immediate quantitative feedback.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <!-- 3. TECHNOLOGY STACK -->
    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <h1>2. Complete Technology Stack & Architecture</h1>
    <p>
        The platform is designed as a modular monorepo to ensure seamless coordination between frontend, backend, and heavy processing services.
    </p>

    <h2>2.1 Frontend Client (apps/web)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>React 18 & Vite:</strong> Used for building a highly responsive Single Page Application (SPA) with fast hot-reloads.</li>
        <li><strong>Tailwind CSS:</strong> Provides utility-first styling for maximum flexibility, customized with the brand's curated design tokens (Indigo Deep, Saffron, Gold, Stone, Ink).</li>
        <li><strong>i18next:</strong> Handles full bilingual localization (Marathi and English) to prioritize rural accessibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Recharts & HTML5 Canvas:</strong> Used for rendering stroke progress charts and custom interactive tracing overlays.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2.2 Backend API (apps/api)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Node.js 20 & Express 5:</strong> Powers the central RESTful API endpoints and WebSocket server.</li>
        <li><strong>Drizzle ORM:</strong> An SQL-first object-relational mapper providing type-safe parameterized queries to prevent SQL injections.</li>
        <li><strong>PGLite:</strong> An in-memory/local WASM PostgreSQL database used in local development ("mock mode") to achieve zero-dependency startup.</li>
        <li><strong>PostgreSQL 18:</strong> The production database provisioned on Render.</li>
        <li><strong>BullMQ & ioredis:</strong> Powers the background job processing pipeline for handling video uploads and notifications.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2.3 Slit-Scan Engine (services/slit-scan)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Python 3.11 & Flask:</strong> Provides a lightweight microservice dedicated to heavy media processing tasks.</li>
        <li><strong>FFmpeg & OpenCV:</strong> Utilized for frame extraction, time-composite slit-scan generation, and drawing waveform rhythm profiling.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2.4 Infrastructure & Cloud Platforms</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Vercel:</strong> Hosts the frontend application, utilizing server rewrites to proxy API requests and bypass CORS issues.</li>
        <li><strong>Render:</strong> Hosts the database instance and the Express backend API service.</li>
        <li><strong>Cloudflare R2:</strong> S3-compatible object storage used for storing user-submitted practice videos and artisan-recorded templates.</li>
        <li><strong>Resend:</strong> Handles automated transaction emails (account verification, password resets).</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <!-- 4. CORE FEATURES -->
    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <h1>3. Core Features & Implementation Details</h1>

    <h2>3.1 Interactive Tracing Canvas</h2>
    <p>
        The tracing canvas is the core learning space. It overlays the user's drawing board with the master's template path.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Webcam Overlay:</strong> Apprentices place their drawing boards under their device's webcam. The canvas draws the digital guides directly over the live camera feed.</li>
        <li><strong>Dynamic Guidelines (Ghost Paths):</strong> Tracing templates (such as Warli triangles or Kolam loops) are rendered as dashed SVG overlay lines.</li>
        <li><strong>Brush Feedback:</strong> The canvas renders a teal trail matching the user's real-time stroke. This helps the user match the path and rhythm of the reference card.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>3.2 Live Evaluation Engine</h2>
    <p>
        Instead of checking just the final image, the engine evaluates the process using two metrics:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Accuracy Matcher:</strong> Computes the spatial deviation between the coordinates of the apprentice's path and the target guide path, rewarding shape fidelity.</li>
        <li><strong>Rhythm Analyzer:</strong> Evaluates the drawing speed consistency. A master's brush flows smoothly, whereas a beginner often hesitates. The engine calculates the velocity standard deviation to score hand control.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>3.3 Role-Based Workflows</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Artisan Publishing:</strong> Master artisans can record a video of themselves drawing a pattern, upload it, specify details (English/Marathi descriptions, difficulty), and publish it as a "Stroke Card".</li>
        <li><strong>Apprentice Practice:</strong> Apprentices browse the library, select cards, practice them, and track their scores over time to build muscle memory.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <!-- 5. SECURITY DESIGN -->
    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <h1>4. Security Architecture</h1>
    <p>
        Security is integrated into all system boundaries to protect artisan intellectual property and ensure platform stability:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Token Security:</strong> JWT Access Tokens are kept strictly in-memory (Zod-validated) and Refresh Tokens are stored in secure <code>httpOnly</code>, <code>SameSite=Strict</code> cookies.</li>
        <li><strong>Role-Based Access Control (RBAC):</strong> Middlewares strictly enforce access rights. Only verified artisans can edit or delete their own Stroke Cards, and admins hold global resource management rights.</li>
        <li><strong>CORS Protection:</strong> Dynamically locks down access to the production frontend URL in production mode, while permitting local host development ports in local mode.</li>
        <li><strong>Audit Logging:</strong> Every system mutation (resource creation, modification, authentication attempts) writes a structured record to the database audit trail to support administrative tracking.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <!-- 6. KEY DESIGN DECISIONS -->
    <!-- ========================================== -->
    <h1>5. Key Design Decisions & Interview Rationale</h1>

    <h2>5.1 Why Decouple the Slit-Scan Engine into Python?</h2>
    <p class="highlight">
        "Processing video files and generating time-composite slit-scan graphics is extremely CPU-heavy. Node.js is single-threaded and would block incoming API requests during video processing. Decoupling this logic to a specialized Python Flask container using FFmpeg ensures our Node.js server remains responsive, and allows scaling the heavy media worker independently."
    </p>

    <h2>5.2 Why PGLite Local Mock Mode?</h2>
    <p class="highlight">
        "Setting up local Docker, Redis, and PostgreSQL databases is a major barrier for new developers or when working offline. By implementing a toggle (USE_LOCAL_MOCKS=true) that spins up PGLite (in-memory PostgreSQL) and in-memory Redis mocks, developers can clone the project and run it instantly with zero external dependencies."
    </p>

    <h2>5.3 Why Vercel Rewrites for the API?</h2>
    <p class="highlight">
        "In standard setups, frontends make requests to a different domain (e.g., api.onrender.com), which triggers CORS preflight OPTIONS requests. This adds latency. By using Vercel rewrites (routing /api/v1/* to Render), Vercel proxies the requests, making the API appear to be on the same origin. This removes CORS issues and speeds up request-response times."
    </p>

</body>
</html>
